---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { costLeaks, costPillars, benchmarkSummary } from "../facts";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Cost savings · Squeezy"
  description="How Squeezy reduces wasted LLM tokens with local code understanding, compact context, bounded tool output, prompt reuse, routing, and visible accounting."
  active="cost"
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-hero-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">cost savings</span>
      <h1>Every model token should have a job.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Squeezy lowers waste by doing local preparation before the model call,
        keeping tool output compact, reusing stable context when providers allow
        it, and showing where tokens go.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-header wide">
      <span class="eyebrow">where cost leaks</span>
      <h2>Agent bills grow when discovery, output, and history pile up.</h2>
      <p>
        A coding agent is expensive when every turn repeats the same repository
        discovery and carries raw output forward. Squeezy attacks those leaks at
        several layers instead of relying on one trick.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid-2">
      {
        costLeaks.map((item) => (
          <article class="card">
            <span class="label">{item.label}</span>
            <h3>{item.title}</h3>
            <p>{item.body}</p>
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section band">
    <div class="section-header wide">
      <span class="eyebrow">method</span>
      <h2>The cost-saving layers in plain language.</h2>
      <p>
        These are the public-facing versions of the mechanisms documented under
        <code>docs/internal/cost-saving/</code>. Each one targets a different
        source of wasted context.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid-3">
      {
        costPillars.map((fact) => (
          <article class="card">
            <span class="label">{fact.label}</span>
            <h3>{fact.title}</h3>
            <p>{fact.body}</p>
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="grid-2">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="eyebrow">proof</span>
        <h2>{benchmarkSummary.codexWins} lower-cost rows on the accepted Codex same-task comparison.</h2>
        <p>
          Benchmarks compare Squeezy with other coding agents on the same repo
          questions and grader. The Codex and Claude Code results are separated
          because they use different tiers and have different maturity.
        </p>
        <div class="actions">
          <a class="button" href="/benchmarks/" data-track-click="cost_benchmarks">Benchmark details</a>
          <a class="button secondary" href="/docs/cost-receipts/" data-track-click="cost_docs">Technical cost docs</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="label">what remains true</span>
        <h3>Savings are not guaranteed on every task.</h3>
        <p>
          Model choice, provider pricing, cache support, task shape, and codebase
          size all matter. The important product claim is that Squeezy has
          multiple implemented ways to reduce waste, plus accounting surfaces to
          inspect the result.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
